Text.Value: 'If your right hand commits injustice, remove it with your left.' If you were truly just, you would not have let yourself be used in such a fashion.
*The god of Justice may not be a liar, but this so-called 'paladin' most certainly is.*
Fine. I'll go quietly. Me and Zariel can settle this face-to-face.
Knock her out. And if she dies in the attempt, all the better.
Rage all you want, Karlach. Burn with the might of the Hells. Zariel will find you, and she will bring you back in pieces.
What do you want, then? A fight? Cause I'll give you one.
I don't have time for this. I didn't come here for a fight, but if you want one, I'm game.
Enough of the theatrics. Who are you really?
'Her Ladyship'. Zariel really has you under her thumb, doesn't she? Pathetic.
Dead it is, then.

EditorData.NodeContext: Right before combat, so vamping up in evilness.

Text.Value: Paladins, ho! Tonight we decorate our hall with this devil's last horn.
Tyr - god of justice, isn't that right? If you really serve him, you'll know I never served Zariel willingly.
Diplomacy! Interesting. But I suppose you were always more complex than Her Ladyship gave you credit for.
Karlach. There you are.
I'm going to start behaving like a devil if you keep calling me one.
I serve Tyr, from now until my dying day. And he has ruled for your execution, devil.
Greetings, motherfucker. Ready to die?
That's right, Karlach. So now as in the Hells. I can see why Her Ladyship wants a murderous brute like you back.

EditorData.NodeContext: stronger in tone, with an edge in his voice; the mask is slipping

Text.Value: Better not to scare off a wild animal until you're ready to spring your trap.
Everything I did in Avernus was against my will. I never wanted to serve Zariel - not for a second.
Avernus was never my home. It was my prison. I'm free now. AND I'M NEVER GOING BACK.
You should've skipped the 'paladins of Tyr' gimmick and faced me for what you are.
I didn't let Zariel do anything. I had no choice.
Then again, maybe she'll just leave you here. Far from home, with an infernal engine for a heart, slowly burning you to ash from the inside.
'Slave' more than 'soldier'. Whatever I've done was against my will.
Paladins, to arms! The devil has found us.
I know what you are. And your threats mean nothing. A servant of Zariel has no power here. The Just God Tyr has claimed these roads.
I'd rather die than look at her fucking face ever again.
*That is no maxim of Tyr - nor a Tyrran belief. The Just God does not hold underlings responsible for the commands of tyrants.*
Attack.
She made you what you are, Karlach. She wants you to come home. Alive, if possible. Dead, if not.
Save your excuses for the City of Judgement. Perhaps Tyr will take pity on you there, for he is the head of justice. We are merely its sword.
I'm no devil. What's this all about?
You lie so easily. But I suppose it is easy for your kind. Tyr warned us not to believe a word out of your mouth, servant of Zariel.
Then your last words will be a lie, will they? I'd expect no different from the likes of you.
Our lord Tyr told us of your guise: The one-horned tiefling hiding the devil within. Servant of Zariel, soldier of the Blood War.
Avernus was never my home. It was my prison. I'm never going back.
The god of Justice never speaks false.
'My Karlach is a cudgel,' she'd say. 'No finesse to speak of, but useful for cracking skulls.'
Did you hear that, fellows? Karlach wants us to let down our guard, shackle her, then burn us to cinders en route back to Avernus.
Tell me who you really are, and maybe we can find another way to settle this.
You've got to reconsider. I don't want to hurt you.
You always were sharper than Her Ladyship gave you credit for.
Whoa now. I think you're confusing me with someone else.

Synopsis: Avatar and Orphan Origin Moment for Karlach meeting the paladins of Tyr that leads into combat.
